****** Registration mandatory for catering purposes**

 

Join us for an exciting Optus Data + AI Event – Unlock the Future of Innovation!

We’re excited to invite you to our upcoming Optus Data + AI Immersion Day on 1 May, where we’ll explore the latest breakthroughs, trends, and applications in artificial intelligence.

A big thank you to our amazing leaders, Belinda Nation and Emma Hartwell, for securing this exciting one-day program with Microsoft and Databricks!

The event is designed to empower Optus employees with the knowledge and tools to leverage data and artificial intelligence for better business outcomes. Diving deeper into this fascinating topic, you’ll learn more about how it’s shaping the future of our industry and technology – and come away feeling more inspired, educated and connected than ever.

Event Details: Optus Data + AI Immersion Day
Date: Thursday 1 May 2025


RSVP: please register via this Microsoft form  


Agenda:

  • Morning Foundational Session: 9am – 12.45pm (all invited)
  • Networking Lunch:  12.45 PM – 1.45 PM
  • Afternoon Focused Streams:  Register session as per your interests.

 

   1. Afternoon Stream 1 (Demo & Gen AI Fundamentals) is suitable for business leaders and people starting out on their Gen AI journey.

 

   2. Afternoon Stream 2 (Getting Started with Gen AI) will provide practical hands-on experience with Gen AI. If you are new to Gen AI, it'll be helpful to build knowledge with Gen AI Fundamentals (about 1 hour) before attending the workshop. In the workshop, a lab coupon code will be provided. You'll need your laptop to complete the labs.

 

   3. Afternoon Stream 3 (AI-Powered Analytics with Power BI) participants must have PBI Desktop installed on their machine as a prerequisite.

 


What to Expect:

  • Keynote speakers - from Optus, Microsoft and Databricks AI experts.
  • Foundational knowledge - AI/BI tools, Gen AI Databricks and Microsoft AI in action.
  • Hands-on experience - with Gen AI tools and Azure OpenAI.
  • Accreditation - in Gen AI Fundamentals, enhancing your professional credentials.
  • Tailored learning - choose from various streams based on your interests and roles.
  • Networking - with experts from Databricks, Microsoft, and peers across different BU’s.
  • Fun activities – Kahoot quizzes with prizes, mini-booths, custom t-shirts & mugs to win!



We look forward to seeing you there and exploring the world of AI together!

Updated time / date due to BU commitments this will now be held on Fri 6 June, 10-11am

 

Sprint 0 - Part 2: Meeting Purpose: "Working Squad – Backlog Forming , Planning and Prioritisation"

This session establishes the foundational structure for the Customer 1st Program:  Stream 3 – Rewards, Incentives, and Consequence Management, ensuring that all squad members understand their roles, responsibilities, and objectives for the upcoming Agile sprints.

To ensure inclusivity for our out of -Sydney office-based stakeholders we are holding this as hybrid meeting

*If you are nominated as an SME Working Squad Member and cannot attend a workshop session, it is your responsibility to find a suitable delegate to represent you and your business function area - for this key Compliance body of work to be delivered.

Apologies in advance:  finding time for these workshops with distributed working squad members is challenging. It is appreciated if you can please make this body of work a priority, your people leader has endorsed your nomination and commitment to this program.

 

Sprint 0 - Our next few Workshops under Sprint 0, planned for

We will –

  1. Review the Priority of each EU item and the guardrails provided from program stream Legal & Assurance sessions (held w/c 2 June) for the Definition of Done (DoD) so we can ensure correct alignment and completeness.
  2. Form the Backlog by;
    • Reviewing and Agreement for the Problem Statement (Epic ‘Big’ User Story) against each EU commitment (~4 in total)
    • Value and Weight the User Stories (Epics and Children) by applying RICE technique (Reach, Impact, Consequences and Effort) i.e. how big or small on a scale of 1-5
    • Create Smaller User Stories (from the Lens of Customer – using the User story format: ‘As a…,  I want … , So that… ‘) for each EU Commitment Epic,
    • Assign a ‘User Story owner’
    • Create and Agree to the ‘Acceptance Criteria’: aligned with the DoD for this User Story to measure how we will accept this user story is complete at the end of the sprint (2wks)
    • Build out User Story Key Tasks and assign task owners for each User Story:  So that the user story can be completed within the agreed Acceptance Criteria and Sprint (2wk cycle)

 

Once the Backlog is formed we will be able to -

  1. Validate the Backlog created, Prioritise and Plan
      • Validate the Backlog: (user stories) against the Problems we need to solve for (EU commitment DoD) –
      • Prioritise the Backlog :based on our “RICE” value / weight given to the User Stories.
      •  Plan and Check: Assigned User Story and Tasks have 1_ an assigned owner and 2) can be achieved by owner’s (working squad members) available capacity within the 2wk sprint to get this completed.
      • Sprint Commitment: Move all committed Users Stories and associated Tasks from the ‘Backlog’ to the ‘Approved/ Ready’ swim lane.

So, we can start Sprinting for Sprint 1 from Wed 11 June.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Re-vision: The Purpose of Sprint 0 is to:

·       Align on Squad Roles & Expectations – Confirming each member’s role, responsibilities, and commitment to driving meaningful outcomes.

·       Introduce and provided guides and links for this contemporary way of working and ensure everyone is aligned on terminology, methodology, and best practices for streamlined collaboration and working with transparency.

·       Define the Sprint Cadence & Approach – Setting up the 2-week sprint cycles, tooling, and ways of working within MS Planner.

·       Create the Squad’s Social Contract – Establishing collaboration principles, accountability measures, and an efficient workflow to ensure success.

·       Define and Validate the Backlog

·       Prioritise, Plan and Assign Task owners to the Approved Backlog ready for Sprint 1

 

What to expect - Outcome of ‘Sprint 0’;

At the end of these Sprint 0 sessions, squad members will feel confident and equipped to begin Sprint 1 with a clear understanding of priorities, execution structure, and expected contributions.

·       A structured squad framework with clarity in roles and expectations.

·       A refined problem statement that aligns with EACH of the EU commitments.

·       A backlog of prioritised work ready for execution in Sprint 1.

·       A functioning (contemporary ways of working) Agile process with defined sprint cadence, tooling, and governance checkpoints.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Thanks in advance for your patience support time and trust as we lean into this work together.

 

Kind regards

Sarah

title: C1, S3 -Rewards, Incentives- Review of our EU Items: Definitions of Done - Milestones and Tasks Discovery
description:
Agenda attached – bring your ‘thinking caps’ along!

 

Purpose:

  • With the view of ‘Future State’ -> i.e. what we need to do to ensure we meet the EU commitment and are compliant, we will be conducting a (structured) review of EU deliverables, against the initial Definition of Done ‘DoD’ from recent Assurance workshops, with a focus on people (resources), processes, systems, and controls to validate our initial Definition of Done (DoD).
  • This meeting will identify any missing milestones, tasks, and potential task owners (aligned to the correct business function) to ensure comprehensive execution and compliance.

 

Outcome:

  • People (Resources): Confirm adequate resourcing, ensuring clear role allocation and ownership within relevant business units. Identify gaps in stakeholder alignment.
  • Processes: Validate end-to-end workflow completeness, ensuring DoD criteria are met and escalation points are clearly defined. Address any missing process steps impacting execution.
  • Systems: Assess system readiness, automation accuracy, and integration dependencies. Identify potential enhancements needed for real-time monitoring and compliance tracking.
  • Controls: Review governance measures, ensuring policies, audit frameworks, and exception-handling mechanisms are aligned with regulatory obligations. Highlight any areas requiring additional oversight.
  • Missing Milestones & Tasks: Identify gaps in task sequencing, stakeholder responsibilities, and deadlines. Assign potential task owners from relevant business units for completion tracking.

 

The information we capture in this session will be used to support the delivery of our work together:

1) Cross check with the Assurance Lead – Jason Hulme we are meeting the commitments and

2) To create and enrich our Stream 3  Working Group Squad JIRA Project Boards that we will be using in our stand ups together to  plan, track, update and report upon.

 

See you then.

title: 10am in The Hub: Meaningful Engagement, Responsibility and Allyship with Shelley Reys, AO
description:
NAIDOC Week 2025 (6-13 July) marks a powerful milestone: 50 years of honouring and elevating Indigenous voices, culture, and resilience. This year’s theme – The Next Generation: Strength, Vision & Legacy – celebrates not only the achievements of the past but the bright future ahead, empowered by the strength of young Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander leaders.

 

On Wednesday 9 July, join us in The Hub at OCS and online for a keynote presentation by Shelley Reys, AO. Shelley will reflect on the current state of reconciliation in Australia, the role of corporate citizenship, and how companies like Optus and each one of us can contribute to reconciliation through genuine allyship.

 

Shelley is a Djiribul woman of far north Queensland and a leader in the corporate, First Nations, and reconciliation spaces for nearly three decades, with a vision “to create a culturally competent Australia, one workplace at a time.”

 

Here’s how you can join us at 10am AEST on Wednesday 9 July:

  • In person at OCS – join us in The Hub
  • MS Teams – click on this link to join the session via your web browser or the Teams app on your mobile.

 

More ways to connect and learn this NAIDOC Week:

  • Our Procurement team is hosting a Supplier Expo in the OCS Plaza following Shelley’s session on Wednesday 9 July (11am-1pm), to showcase and demonstrate the capabilities of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander suppliers including Supply Nation, Australia’s largest database of verified Indigenous businesses, as well as Indigeco, yarn.com.au, Binjang Tea and KARI. John James Grant, a talented First Nation Wiradjuri singer-songwriter and musician from Sydney, will be performing an acoustic set, and you can sample native Australian-flavoured refreshments from Dreamtime Tuka and Binjang Tea, proudly majority owned Aboriginal companies.
  • Cooking is one of the world’s oldest technologies. This NAIDOC Week, we’re hosting hands-on workshops at OCA (Wednesday 2 July) and OCB and OCM (Wednesday 9 July), giving you the opportunity to learn more about the ingredients and cooking techniques of the world's longest practiced science of sustainability, passed down through generations of First Nations people. Spaces are limited – register now. Registration is open to Optus employees and contractors. If all places are taken, please join the waitlist.  
  • Expressions of Interest are open now until mid-July for the Jawun corporate secondment program. Before you apply, please make sure you read all the information, which can be found here.

 

Our team is dedicated to ensuring everyone can fully experience our events. If you have any accessibility needs or requirements, please reach out to events@optus.com.au.

title: On Leave
Celebrating Optus Youth Week with The Daily Aus
description:
We’re recognising International Youth Day with a keynote presentation from Sam Koslowski and Zara Seidler, co-founders of The Daily Aus – brought to you by the Young Professionals Network.  

Join us to celebrate young innovators driving meaningful and inclusive futures, while inspiring our community to cultivate the next generation of Optus leaders and game changers. 

The Daily Aus is a youth focused social media-first news provider reshaping the way young people consume news. The platform produces digestible public interest news for more than 2.5 million young Australians every month. Sam and Zara will share their story and how they’ve become a trusted source of news for a new generation in a legacy industry.

Here’s how you can join us at 11am AEST on Tuesday 19 August: 

  • In person at OCS – join us in the Auditorium. 
  • MS Teams – click on this link to join the session via your web browser or the Teams app on your mobile. 

We’re celebrating International Youth Day with our first Youth Week from 12-19 August. Here are more ways to connect and learn throughout the week: 

  • Career catapult - join us for a roundtable mentoring session with Optus leaders and our next gen game changers. Register here. 
  • Early careers networking BBQ – a social BBQ to network with early career talent across the business, growing connections and making new friends.  
  • Inspiring stories – hear from young professionals across Optus as they share their story, their growth and how a career journey can lead you down many paths. Keep an eye out on Viva Engage. 


We're dedicated to ensuring everyone can fully experience our events. If you have any accessibility needs or requirements, please reach out to us at events@optus.com.au.

Without limiting paragraph 6.5, Optus will, by no later than 6 months from the Commencement Date and for the remaining duration of the Term, ensure that any remuneration and incentives for Optus Sales Staff (including staff with direct management responsibilities for other Optus Sales Staff) at an Optus Operated Store are consistent with the Telecommunications Consumer Protections Code (TCP Code) (as amended from time to time) and subject to the following conditions:
  1. customer service and compliance gateways must be met by the relevant Optus Operated Store each month before any commission is payable to a salesperson in respect of that month. These customer service and compliance gateways must appropriately reward positive consumer interactions and compliance with key quality control metrics, which will incentivise good sales practices; 
  2. for Optus Sales Staff employed at Optus Operated Stores located in the Northern Territory, any incentives payable will be based solely on customer service and compliance gateways;
  3. total commissions payable to a salesperson in any period must be no more than 150% of the salesperson’s variable target for that period (which is 15% of the salesperson’s base pay);
  4. payment of sales based related commissions (whether volume or revenue related) will be deferred for 3 months from the date of the applicable sale;
Kate Aitken
Joel Rethore
Henry Willmington
Frances Martin
Yolanda Chora
6 months from EU commencement date.

  1. if Optus, in investigating any conduct of a salesperson, identifies that there is evidence that a salesperson has engaged in improper sales practices, including any Improper Sales Conduct, Optus must withhold an amount equal to 3 times the total commission for the affected transaction from any future commissions otherwise payable to that salesperson.   2. if a salesperson is determined by the Compliance Officer (or its delegate) to have engaged in improper sales practices, including any Improper Sales Conduct, Optus must deduct an amount equal to 3 times the total commission payable to the salesperson in relation to the affected transaction from any future commissions otherwise payable to that salesperson;

Joel Rethore
Henry Willmington
Frances Martin
Yolanda Chora
6 months from EU commencement date.
